questions.explanation:
Angular is a powerful front-end framework that provides developers with a structured approach to building web applications. It offers a component-based architecture where each component manages its own template, logic, and styling. The framework leverages TypeScript, which adds strong typing and object-oriented programming features to JavaScript. Key advantages include two-way data binding, dependency injection, and comprehensive tooling support through Angular CLI.

Example of a basic Angular component:
```typescript
@Component({
  selector: 'app-example',
  template: '<h1>{{title}}</h1>'
})
export class ExampleComponent {
  title = 'My Angular App';
}
```

Data binding is a core feature of Angular that simplifies the synchronization of data between the component and the view. Angular supports multiple binding types: interpolation, property binding, event binding, and two-way data binding. This approach reduces boilerplate code and makes data management more intuitive.

Example of different data binding types:
```typescript
// Interpolation
<p>{{username}}</p>

// Property Binding
<img [src]='imageUrl'>

// Event Binding
<button (click)='saveData()'>

// Two-Way Binding
<input [(ngModel)]='username'>
```

Angular's architecture promotes a modular and scalable approach to web application development. Modules organize related functionality, components manage specific UI sections, services handle data and business logic, and routing enables navigation between different views. Dependency injection is a key mechanism that allows efficient management of component dependencies and promotes loose coupling.

Example of a basic Angular module structure:
```typescript
@NgModule({
  declarations: [AppComponent, UserComponent],
  imports: [BrowserModule, RouterModule],
  providers: [UserService],
  bootstrap: [AppComponent]
})
export class AppModule { }
```

Dependency Injection is a core Angular mechanism that allows components to receive their dependencies without creating them directly. It promotes loose coupling, improves code reusability, and simplifies testing by managing object creation and lifecycle. In practice, this means services and dependencies can be easily injected into components using constructor injection.

```typescript
@Injectable()
class UserService {
  getUsers() { /* logic */ }
}

@Component({
  selector: 'user-list',
})
class UserListComponent {
  constructor(private userService: UserService) {}
}
```

Angular modules serve as organizational containers that group related functionality. They help manage dependencies, control complexity, and provide a clear structure for application components. Modules are defined using the @NgModule decorator and can import other modules, declare components, and provide services.

```typescript
@NgModule({
  declarations: [UserComponent, ProfileComponent],
  imports: [CommonModule, RouterModule],
  providers: [UserService]
})
export class UserModule { }
```

Event binding in Angular provides a declarative way to respond to user interactions directly in templates. The framework simplifies connecting DOM events to component methods, making interaction handling more intuitive and readable.

```html
<button (click)="handleClick($event)">Click me</button>
```

```typescript
class MyComponent {
  handleClick(event: MouseEvent) {
    // Handle click event
  }
}
```

Angular provides two primary approaches to form handling. Template-Driven Forms are simpler and use two-way data binding, while Reactive Forms offer more programmatic control and are better suited for complex validation scenarios. To use forms effectively, developers must import either FormsModule or ReactiveFormsModule and configure form controls appropriately. 

Example of a basic Reactive Form setup:
```typescript
this.myForm = this.formBuilder.group({
  username: ['', Validators.required],
  email: ['', [Validators.required, Validators.email]]
});
```

HttpClient is the recommended method for making HTTP requests in Angular, offering a powerful and flexible approach to server communication. It returns observables, supports typed requests, and includes features like interceptors and easy error handling.

Example of a typical HTTP GET request:
```typescript
getUsers() {
  return this.http.get<User[]>('api/users');
}
```
